				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${E}_{VB}(Ce{O}_{2})={E}_{g}-{E}_{CB}(Ce{O}_{2})$$\end{document}where χ is electronegativity of the sample (Here, χ = 5.56 eV for CeO2), Ec and Eg represent free electrons’ energy on the hydrogen scale (~4.5 eV) and the energy gap of CeO2 (~3 eV) respectively. The estimated values of the CB and VB positions in CeO2 NCs are −0.67 and 2.79 eV respectively. Accordingly, the CB and VB edge positions in Zn doped CeO2 NCs are found to be −0.73 and 2.85 eV respectively. The values of VB positions for pure and Zn doped CeO2 NCs are higher than the water reduction potential and indicate that these materials are good and may a potential candidate for photocatalytic O2 production.

